def: A word or form of speech thrown in to express emotion orfeeling, as O! Alas! Ha ha! Begone! etc. Compare Exclamation.An interjection implies a meaning which it would require a wholegrammatical sentence to expound, and it may be regarded as therudiment of such a sentence. But it is a confusion of thought to rankit among the parts of speech. Earle.How now! interjections Why, then, some be of laughing, as, ah, ha,he! Shak.
A headdress of false hair, usually covering the whole head, andrepresenting the natural hair; a wig. Shak.
To marry; to unite in marriage; to wed. [R.] "Man thuswedlocked." Milton.
On the bare back of a horse, without using a saddle; as, toride bareback.
The sound of the voice as heard through a stethoscope when thelatter is placed upon the larynx.
Greatly; enormously; shamefully; as, egregiously cheated.
Having the form of liber, or resembling liber. Libriform cells,peculiar wood cells which are very slender and relatively thick-walled, and occasionally are furnished with bordered pits. Goodale.
The act of interpreting erroneously; a mistaken interpretation.
